---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { githubUrl } from "../data/site";
const raw = `${githubUrl}/blob/main`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Documentation"
  description="A source-linked introduction to the pre-release Kingdom of PAL architecture, workflow, agent registry and approval model."
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow">Documentation · Pre-release</p><h1>
        Start with the organisational layer.
      </h1><p class="lead">
        Kingdom of PAL is currently a contract-first scaffold. These docs
        explain what exists in the repository and what remains future
        functionality.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell content-grid">
      <aside class="side-index" aria-label="Documentation topics">
        <a href="#status">Current status</a><a href="#architecture"
          >Architecture</a
        ><a href="#workflow-definition">Campaign workflow</a><a
          href="#contracts">Contracts</a
        ><a href="#sources">Source files</a>
      </aside><div class="prose">
        <section id="status">
          <p class="eyebrow">Read this first</p><h2>
            There is no runnable release yet.
          </h2><p>
            The repository defines the organisation, registry, schemas, policies
            and workflows. It does not yet run agents, persist memory, deploy
            services or provide the proposed <code>kingdom</code> command-line interface.
          </p><div class="demo-banner" role="note">
            <strong>Future interface</strong><span
              >Any command examples in repository materials describe a target
              experience, not something visitors can run today.</span
            >
          </div>
        </section>
        <section id="architecture">
          <p class="eyebrow">Architecture</p><h2>
            Independent agents. Shared rules.
          </h2><p>
            The kingdom repository owns the Founder's Charter, registry, shared
            contracts, approval policies and workflow definitions. Agent
            implementations remain independently versioned and are intended to
            collaborate through stable contracts rather than internal coupling.
          </p><div class="code-block">
            Founder request ↓ Founder's Charter + approval policy ↓ Orin selects
            context and coordinates ↓ Scribe produces · Rick reviews · Bastion
            diagnoses ↓ Founder approval → intended audit + memory
          </div>
        </section>
        <section id="workflow-definition">
          <p class="eyebrow">Primary workflow</p><h2>
            Governed community campaign
          </h2><p>
            The workflow definition contains five explicit steps and three
            actors: Orin, Scribe and Rick, followed by a founder checkpoint and
            an Orin-authored summary.
          </p><div class="code-block">
            identify-need / Orin / low risk → create-campaign / Scribe / low
            risk → security-review / Rick / medium risk → founder-approval /
            Founder / medium risk → record-outcome / Orin / low risk
          </div><p><a class="button" href="/demo">Watch the demo</a></p>
        </section>
        <section id="contracts">
          <p class="eyebrow">Contract-first integration</p><h2>
            Handoffs have schemas.
          </h2><p>
            Versioned JSON Schemas define task requests, task results, approval
            requests and approval decisions. The registry declares which
            contracts each agent accepts and returns.
          </p><p>
            This is architectural evidence, not proof that cross-repository
            runtime handoffs are operational today.
          </p>
        </section>
        <section id="sources">
          <p class="eyebrow">Source of truth</p><h2>
            Verify the model in the repository.
          </h2><div class="source-list">
            <a class="source-link" href={`${raw}/README.md`}
              ><span>Product status and principles</span><code>README.md ↗</code
              ></a
            ><a class="source-link" href={`${raw}/agent-registry.yaml`}
              ><span>Agents and lifecycle rules</span><code
                >agent-registry.yaml ↗</code
              ></a
            ><a class="source-link" href={`${raw}/founders-charter/CHARTER.md`}
              ><span>Mission and human authority</span><code>CHARTER.md ↗</code
              ></a
            ><a
              class="source-link"
              href={`${raw}/approval-policies/default.yaml`}
              ><span>Risk and approval rules</span><code>default.yaml ↗</code
              ></a
            ><a
              class="source-link"
              href={`${raw}/workflow-definitions/community-campaign.yaml`}
              ><span>Primary demonstration workflow</span><code
                >community-campaign.yaml ↗</code
              ></a
            ><a
              class="source-link"
              href={`${raw}/shared-contracts/task-request.schema.json`}
              ><span>Shared task contract</span><code
                >task-request.schema.json ↗</code
              ></a
            >
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
  <section class="section section-dark final-cta">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">See it as an outcome</p><h2>
        Architecture earns trust. The workflow earns attention.
      </h2><div class="button-row">
        <a class="button" href="/demo">Watch the demo</a><a
          class="button button-secondary"
          href={githubUrl}>View on GitHub ↗</a
        >
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
